  <tr> 
    <td class="text"><!-- #BeginEditable "caption" -->Scoria, a locally available 
      volcanic rock, was used for pottery temper by the villagers who lived at 
      Hank's site. The local scoria is a dark red to black, porous-looking rock 
      full of little air pockets that form tiny holes along its edges. It is, 
      in fact, slag ejected out of a volcano during an eruption. The most important 
      characteristics of the local scoria are that the weathered nodules are easy 
      to crush up, and the tiny bits of rock have sharp angular edges and make 
      excellent temper for binding clay together in pottery making. Photo by Doug 
      Boyd.<!-- #EndEditable --></td>
